The precise synthesis of CDs has been a key area of scientific research, with synthesis methods categorized into “Top-down” and “Bottom-up” approaches based on the carbon source (Fig. 1
                     ) [36]. The “top-down” method uses chemical processes to extract tiny CDs from large carbon sources, including CNTs, carbon fibers and graphite rods [37–39]. Conversely, the “Bottom-up” approach involves the synthesis of CDs from small carbon sources in molecular ionic states, with small organic molecules or oligomers playing a key role in the synthesis process [40–42]. Continuing on, we'll examine the subtleties of the classic “top-down” and “bottom-up” synthesis approaches, and offer a side-by-side comparison of their strengths and weaknesses as outlined in Table 1
                     .
